						<summary>

						<p>On the west wall, central shrine, Anantēśvarasvāmin temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Year 10: 981 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>It is in Sanskrit language engraved in Grantha characters.</p>						

						<p>Begins with obeisance to Lord Śiva. It records that an individual Nampieṉbāṉ, son of Mahāmati, son of Nakkan, son of Trivikrama, apparently set up a garden and <hi rend="italic">śāla</hi> for feeding one hundred brāhmaṇas daily possibly at the request of his wife Śīlachuḍar. It is also described that the latter belonged to a noble family and was a woman of great beauty. For carrying out this benefaction, the donor Nambieṉbāṉ ceded the village Tuṟaiyūr-kiḷḷikkuḍi.</p>						

						</summary>
